  "local_port": 38940,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some AngularJS interview questions?",
  "response": "Here are some common AngularJS interview questions along with their answers:\n\n1. What is AngularJS?\n\nAngularJS is a JavaScript-based open-source front-end web application framework mainly maintained by Google and a community of individuals and corporations to address many of the challenges encountered in developing single-page applications.\n\n2. Explain the key features of AngularJS.\n\n- Two-way data binding\n- MVC (Model-View-Controller) architecture\n- Directives\n- Templates\n- Dependency Injection\n- Services\n- Filters\n- Routing\n\n3. What is two-way data binding in AngularJS?\n\nTwo-way data binding is a mechanism where any change in the model updates the view and vice versa. It ensures that the model and the view are always synchronized.\n\n4. What are directives in AngularJS?\n\nDirectives are markers on a DOM element that tell AngularJS to attach a specified behavior to that DOM element or even transform the DOM element and its children.\n\n5. What are some commonly used built-in directives in AngularJS?\n\n- ng-app: Defines and links an AngularJS application to HTML.\n- ng-model: Binds the value of HTML controls (input, select, textarea) to application data.\n- ng-bind: Binds the innerHTML of an element to application data.\n- ng-repeat: Repeats a set of HTML elements for each item in a collection.\n- ng-show/ng-hide: Conditionally shows or hides an element based on an expression.\n\n6. What is the difference between ng-show/ng-hide and ng-if?\n\nng-show/ng-hide add or remove the CSS display property to show or hide elements, while ng-if completely removes or recreates an element in the DOM based on an expression.\n\n7. What is a scope in AngularJS?\n\nA scope is an object that refers to the application model. It acts as a context for expressions and watches changes to these expressions to execute actions when changes occur.\n\n8. Explain the difference between $scope and scope.\n\n$scope is a service provided by AngularJS that acts as a glue between the controller and the view. It is used to expose variables and functions to the view. On the other hand, 'scope' is a parameter that can be passed to directives to create new scopes.\n\n9. What are services in AngularJS?\n\nServices are singleton objects or functions that are used to carry out specific tasks in AngularJS applications. They can be injected into controllers, directives, or other services.\n\n10. Name some commonly used built-in services in AngularJS.\n\n- $http: Used to make AJAX calls to external servers.\n- $timeout: A wrapper for the window.setTimeout function.\n- $interval: A wrapper for the window.setInterval function.\n- $location: Used to interact with the browser's URL.\n- $q: Provides a promise-based API for asynchronous operations.\n\n11. What is dependency injection in AngularJS?\n\nDependency injection is a design pattern in which an object receives other objects that it depends on. AngularJS uses dependency injection to provide components such as controllers, services, or directives with the dependencies they need.\n\n12. What is the difference between a factory and a service in AngularJS?\n\nA factory is a design pattern used to create objects. In AngularJS, a factory is a function that returns a value or an object. A service, on the other hand, is a constructor function that gets instantiated with the 'new' keyword. Both are used to create singleton objects, but a factory provides more flexibility in object creation.\n\n13. What are filters in AngularJS?\n\nFilters are used to format data displayed to the user. They can be used in expressions, directives like ng-repeat, or in services. Some built-in filters include currency, date, uppercase, lowercase, and orderBy.\n\n14. How does routing work in AngularJS?\n\nAngularJS uses the ngRoute module to implement routing. The $routeProvider is used to define routes, and the $location service is used to interact with the browser's URL. When a user navigates to a URL, AngularJS matches the URL against the defined routes and loads the appropriate template and controller.\n\n15. What is the role of the $rootScope in AngularJS?\n\n$rootScope is the top-most scope in the AngularJS application's scope hierarchy. Every application has a $rootScope which can be accessed via the $injector. It is useful for sharing data or functionality across the entire application.\n\nThese questions cover a wide range of topics in AngularJS and should provide a good starting point for interview preparation. However, it's important to have a deep understanding of AngularJS concepts and to be able to apply them in real-world scenarios.",
